---
title: Designing websites for Google — and for the AI that answers instead
excerpt: Search is splitting in two - classic Google results and AI assistants that read, summarize and quote the web. Both reward the same thing - a fast site with clean, legible HTML. Here's what "designed to be found" means in 2026, in plain language.
date: '2026-07-30'
category: AI
draft: true
---

For twenty years, "being found online" meant one thing: rank on Google. That era isn't over — but it now has a twin. A growing share of your customers never see a results page at all. They ask an AI assistant, and the assistant reads the web, forms an answer, and *quotes its sources*. Your website is either quotable or it's invisible.

Here's the good news that surprises most clients: you don't need two strategies. Google's crawler and the AI assistants reward mostly the same underlying qualities. The bad news: most websites — especially page-builder websites — have none of them.

## What both audiences want

Strip away the jargon and both Google and the AI systems are readers with no patience. They want:

- **Speed.** A slow site gets crawled less, ranked lower, and abandoned by humans. Static, hand-coded pages are effectively instant, because the page exists as a finished document before anyone asks for it.
- **Legible structure.** Machines don't *look* at your site; they read the HTML. If your headings are real headings, your text is real text, and the document's structure mirrors its meaning, a machine can lift the answer straight out of it. If your content is trapped in a soup of generated wrappers — or worse, only appears after JavaScript runs — you're asking the reader to do work it will often decline to do.
- **Answers, stated plainly.** Both Google's snippets and AI summaries favor pages that state the answer, then elaborate. It's why every case study and post on this site opens with the point instead of a warm-up paragraph.

## The invisible layer most sites skip

Beyond the visible page, a well-built site carries a layer of metadata written purely for machines. It's the part no one sees and everyone underestimates:

- **Structured data** — a machine-readable description of who you are, what you offer, what this page is, how the FAQ questions and answers pair up. It's how you tell Google *exactly* what it's looking at instead of hoping it guesses.
- **An llms.txt index** — a plain-text map of the site written for AI assistants, listing every page with a one-line summary. New, cheap to provide, and almost nobody does it.
- **Markdown twins** — on this site, every article and case study also exists as a clean markdown document at the same address. An AI that wants the text gets the text, with zero chrome in the way.

None of this is visible design. All of it is design — decisions about how the site presents itself to its most influential readers.

## Why page builders fail this test

I've made the [general case against page builders](/journal/why-we-hand-code-websites) elsewhere, but the search angle deserves its own sentence: a page builder generates markup for the convenience of the builder, not the reader. Bloated wrappers, client-side rendering, an SEO plugin bolted on top fighting the theme for control of the head tag — every layer adds noise between your content and the machine trying to read it. You can rank with a builder site. You're just running the race with a parachute on.

## What this means if you're not technical

You don't need to learn any of these words. You need to ask whoever builds your next site three questions:

1. *Is the site static or does it render in the browser?* (You want: static.)
2. *Will the structured data be written per page, or does a plugin guess?* (You want: per page.)
3. *Can an AI assistant read every page as clean text?* (You want: yes — and a builder who understands the question.)

The web's front door is being rebuilt in real time. The sites that walk through it aren't the prettiest ones — they're the fastest, clearest, most legible ones. Prettiness we can also do. But legibility is the part your customers will never see and always feel.

